      "content": "The nonviolent approach was strategically brilliant because it leveraged the moral authority of the nation against its own racist laws, making it politically impossible for the establishment to ignore. By maintaining discipline in the face of violence, activists forced the federal government to intervene, which was the only way to overcome entrenched state resistance. While some argue it allowed for slow progress, the moral pressure generated by nonviolence was the engine that compelled necessary, albeit imperfect, legislative change.",
